---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import CTA from '../components/CTA.astro';
---

<Base title="Get Started">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-20">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Get started with Baxter</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
      Baxter is a plain-text harness — a folder you drop into any project. No accounts, no subscriptions, no special tooling. You need git, an AI coding tool (Claude Code, Cursor, or similar), and your project's source code.
    </p>

    <!-- What you'll have at the end -->
    <div class="mt-8 rounded-xl border border-primary-200 bg-primary-50 p-5 dark:border-primary-800/40 dark:bg-primary-900/10">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary-800 dark:text-primary-300">What you'll have at the end of this guide</p>
      <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span>✓</span><span>Baxter installed and reading your codebase</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span>✓</span><span>Your first artefact generated and saved to git</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span>✓</span><span>A clear understanding of how to invoke each artefact type</span></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- coderepo callout — must be unmissable -->
    <div class="mt-10 rounded-xl border-2 border-primary-500 bg-primary-50 p-6 dark:border-primary-700 dark:bg-primary-950/30">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400">Most important step — where does my code go?</p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">→ <code class="text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400">coderepo/</code></p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Copy or symlink your project's source code into the <code class="rounded bg-white px-1 dark:bg-zinc-900">coderepo/</code> folder. Baxter reads it to verify that every artefact — BRD, TIP, test case — uses real module names, real field names, and real routes. Without this, Baxter cannot check anything.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-primary-200 bg-zinc-950 dark:border-primary-800">
        <pre class="p-4 text-xs text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed">agentic-ba/
├── <span class="text-primary-400 font-bold">coderepo/</span>        ← YOUR PROJECT SOURCE CODE HERE
│   └── (your app, API, schema, migrations…)
├── artefacts/
│   ├── issues/      ← bugs, changes, AI features
│   └── other/       ← requirements, product-docs, implementation, test-suites, diagrams
├── templates/
│   ├── issues/      ← BR, CR, AI
│   └── other/       ← BRD, PD, TIP, TC, DIA
└── CLAUDE.md</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-700 bg-zinc-950">
        <div class="border-b border-zinc-800 px-4 py-2 text-xs text-zinc-500">three ways to add your code</div>
        <pre class="p-4 text-xs text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed"># Copy your project in
cp -r /path/to/your/project coderepo/

# Or symlink it (keeps one copy on disk)
ln -s /path/to/your/project coderepo/src

# Or clone a sub-repo into it
git clone https://github.com/your-org/your-project coderepo/</pre>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-500">
        <code class="rounded bg-white px-1 dark:bg-zinc-900">coderepo/</code> is gitignored — your source code stays private and is never committed to the agentic-ba repo.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 space-y-12">

      <!-- Step 1 -->
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-primary-600 text-sm font-bold text-white">1</span>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Clone or copy the harness</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-200 bg-zinc-950 dark:border-zinc-700">
          <pre class="p-4 text-sm text-zinc-300">git clone https://github.com/glovarix/agentic-ba.git
cd agentic-ba</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
          Or copy the folder into an existing project repo. The harness is self-contained — it does not affect your project's code or CI.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 2 -->
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-primary-600 text-sm font-bold text-white">2</span>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Add your codebase</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-200 bg-zinc-950 dark:border-zinc-700">
          <pre class="p-4 text-sm text-zinc-300">cp -r /path/to/your/project coderepo/</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
          Baxter reads <code class="rounded bg-zinc-100 px-1 dark:bg-zinc-800">coderepo/</code> to verify module names, field names, and routes in every artefact before saving. If your codebase is large, a symlink works just as well.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 3 -->
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-primary-600 text-sm font-bold text-white">3</span>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Open in your AI agent</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
          Open the folder in Claude Code, Cursor, or VS Code with GitHub Copilot. Baxter's instructions are already in the right file for each tool — the agent loads them automatically with no setup.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-700">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead class="border-b border-zinc-200 bg-zinc-50 dark:border-zinc-700 dark:bg-zinc-900">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Tool</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Instruction file loaded automatically</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-100 dark:divide-zinc-800">
              {[
                { tool: 'Claude Code', file: 'CLAUDE.md' },
                { tool: 'Cursor', file: '.cursor/rules/baxter.mdc' },
                { tool: 'GitHub Copilot', file: '.github/copilot-instructions.md' },
              ].map((row) => (
                <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-zinc-950">
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-200">{row.tool}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400">{row.file}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
          All three files are identical. A pre-commit hook keeps them in sync — edit <code class="rounded bg-zinc-100 px-1 dark:bg-zinc-800">CLAUDE.md</code> and the others update automatically on your next commit. Run this once after cloning to activate it:
        </p>
        <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-200 bg-zinc-950 dark:border-zinc-700">
          <pre class="p-4 text-sm text-zinc-300">git config core.hooksPath .githooks</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 4 -->
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-primary-600 text-sm font-bold text-white">4</span>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Paste a request — any raw text</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-200 bg-zinc-950 dark:border-zinc-700">
          <div class="border-b border-zinc-800 px-4 py-2 text-xs text-zinc-500">example requests — paste exactly as received</div>
          <div class="space-y-3 p-4 text-sm text-zinc-300">
            <p>"The login page returns a 500 error when the user submits without a password"</p>
            <p class="border-t border-zinc-800 pt-3">"Write up the BRD for care plan cloning"</p>
            <p class="border-t border-zinc-800 pt-3">"I need test cases for the vitals module — mandatory fields and role access"</p>
            <p class="border-t border-zinc-800 pt-3">"Add a print to PDF button to the patient profile page"</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
          Baxter classifies the request, tells you which template it will use, and asks for a one-word confirmation before generating anything. You can reply with the artefact code (e.g. <code class="rounded bg-zinc-100 px-1 dark:bg-zinc-800">BR</code>), a number, or just <code class="rounded bg-zinc-100 px-1 dark:bg-zinc-800">proceed</code>.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>

    <!-- Sample artefacts callout -->
    <div class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-emerald-200 bg-emerald-50 p-6 dark:border-emerald-800/40 dark:bg-emerald-900/10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400">Already in the repo — ready to explore</p>
      <h3 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Sample artefacts from an imaginary Todo App</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        The repo includes a set of sample artefacts generated for a fictional Todo App — so you can see exactly what Baxter produces before writing your first request. None of these are from a real project; they exist purely as output examples.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-emerald-200 bg-white p-3 dark:border-emerald-800/30 dark:bg-zinc-900">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400">📖 Product Documentation</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400"><code>artefacts/other/product-docs/</code></p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">Full PD for the imaginary Todo App — modules, roles, API routes, data model, known limitations</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-emerald-200 bg-white p-3 dark:border-emerald-800/30 dark:bg-zinc-900">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400">🧪 Test Cases (13 total)</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400"><code>artefacts/other/test-suites/</code></p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">Authentication, Todos, and Tags — happy path, negative, role-based, and edge cases</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-emerald-200 bg-white p-3 dark:border-emerald-800/30 dark:bg-zinc-900">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400">📋 BRD + TIP</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400"><code>artefacts/other/requirements/</code> &amp; <code>implementation/</code></p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">Due Date Reminders — requirements document and matching implementation plan</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-emerald-200 bg-white p-3 dark:border-emerald-800/30 dark:bg-zinc-900">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400">🐛 BR · 🔄 CR · 🤖 AI · 📐 DIA</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400"><code>artefacts/issues/</code> &amp; <code>other/</code></p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">One sample of each remaining artefact type — all for the same fictional app</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Try it now callout -->
    <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl border border-indigo-200 bg-indigo-50 p-6 dark:border-indigo-800/40 dark:bg-indigo-900/10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-indigo-700 dark:text-indigo-400">Try every artefact right now — no setup needed</p>
      <h3 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">The imaginary Todo App is your sandbox</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Open the repo in Claude Code or Cursor and paste any of the prompts below. The sample artefacts give Baxter enough context about the fictional Todo App to classify, generate, and save — no real codebase required. Add your own codebase to <code class="rounded bg-white px-1 dark:bg-zinc-900">coderepo/</code> when you are ready to work on a real project.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-5 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
        {[
          { icon: '📋', label: 'BRD', prompt: '"Write up the requirements for adding a due date field to todos"' },
          { icon: '📖', label: 'PD', prompt: '"Document the authentication module"' },
          { icon: '🏗️', label: 'TIP', prompt: '"Write an implementation plan for adding tag colours to the todo list view"' },
          { icon: '🧪', label: 'TC', prompt: '"Generate test cases for the Tags module"' },
          { icon: '🐛', label: 'BR', prompt: '"The Tags endpoint returns 500 when a duplicate name is submitted"' },
          { icon: '🔄', label: 'CR', prompt: '"Add a bulk delete option to the todos list"' },
          { icon: '🤖', label: 'AI', prompt: '"We need an AI feature to auto-suggest tags based on the todo title"' },
          { icon: '📐', label: 'DIA', prompt: '"Diagram the todo creation flow from API request to database"' },
        ].map((item) => (
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-indigo-200 bg-white p-3 dark:border-indigo-800/30 dark:bg-zinc-900">
            <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-indigo-700 dark:text-indigo-400">{item.icon} {item.label}</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs italic text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">{item.prompt}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Baxter will classify each request, confirm the template, generate the artefact with a full sanity check, and ask before saving — exactly as it would on your real project.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Artefact invocation reference -->
    <div class="mt-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">What to say for each artefact</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Baxter uses signal words to classify your request. You never need to name the template — just describe what you need. The table below shows the words Baxter listens for.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-700">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead class="border-b border-zinc-200 bg-zinc-50 dark:border-zinc-700 dark:bg-zinc-900">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Artefact</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Signal words Baxter listens for</th>
              <th class="hidden px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white sm:table-cell">Template used</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-100 dark:divide-zinc-800">
            {[
              { icon: '🐛', name: 'Bug Report (BR)', signals: '"not working", "broken", "error", "404", "500", "crash", "fails"', template: 'issues/BR.md' },
              { icon: '🔄', name: 'Change Request (CR)', signals: '"add", "new", "improve", "enhance", "change", "feature request"', template: 'issues/CR.md' },
              { icon: '🤖', name: 'AI Feature (AI)', signals: '"AI feature", "auto-fill", "auto-generate", "suggest", "LLM"', template: 'issues/AI.md' },
              { icon: '📋', name: 'Business Requirements (BRD) — pre-dev', signals: '"BRD", "business requirements", "spec for", "write up the requirements"', template: 'other/BRD.md' },
              { icon: '📖', name: 'Product Documentation (PD) — post-dev', signals: '"PD", "document the module", "how it works", "what was built"', template: 'other/PD.md' },
              { icon: '🏗️', name: 'Implementation Plan (TIP)', signals: '"TIP", "implementation plan", "how to build", "dev plan"', template: 'other/TIP.md' },
              { icon: '🧪', name: 'Test Cases (TC)', signals: '"test cases", "test suite", "QA cases", "test steps"', template: 'other/TC.md' },
              { icon: '📐', name: 'Diagram (DIA)', signals: '"diagram", "flowchart", "mermaid", "draw", "visualise"', template: 'other/DIA.md' },
            ].map((row) => (
              <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-zinc-950">
                <td class="px-4 py-3">
                  <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                    <span>{row.icon}</span>
                    <span class="font-medium text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-200">{row.name}</span>
                  </div>
                </td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">{row.signals}</td>
                <td class="hidden px-4 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400 sm:table-cell">{row.template}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Baxter applies the first match in priority order. If nothing matches, Baxter asks you one clarifying question.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Tips for beginners -->
    <div class="mt-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Tips for getting the best results</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
        {[
          {
            title: 'You never need to structure your input',
            body: 'Paste raw emails, Slack messages, voice transcripts, or Google Doc excerpts exactly as they are. Baxter extracts what it needs. The messier the input, the more value Baxter adds.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Coderepo is the key to verification',
            body: 'Without coderepo/, Baxter can still generate artefacts — but it cannot verify module names, field names, or routes. For production teams, always add your codebase.',
          },
          {
            title: 'You review. You approve. You commit.',
            body: 'Baxter always asks for confirmation before generating, and always presents the artefact for review before saving. Nothing is written without your sign-off. Your name goes in the revision history.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Templates are yours to change',
            body: 'Open any file in templates/issues/ or templates/other/ and edit the sections to match your team\'s standards. Baxter reads whatever is on disk — no config required.',
          },
          {
            title: 'One request at a time',
            body: 'If a client request contains multiple needs (e.g. a bug and a feature), handle them separately. Paste the bug first, then the feature request. Baxter handles one artefact per conversation.',
          },
        ].map((tip) => (
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-zinc-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-zinc-800 dark:bg-zinc-900">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">{tip.title}</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">{tip.body}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <CTA />
</Base>
